    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to question that; the fear that congestion pricing acts as a regressive tax is not just a political talking point but a well-documented economic concern. Proponents argue that because the fees are significantly higher for those driving than for those taking transit, the program inherently penalizes working-class commuters who lack the luxury of living near subway stations or the option to walk to work. While the revenue is theoretically reinvested into public transit to lower long-term costs, many experts agree that without very specific, targeted subsidies for low-income drivers, the immediate financial burden feels like a tax on the poor rather than a fair investment in the city.",
